		<item>
		<title>MCR 029: Building a Platform to Reach Your Tribe</title>
		<link>http://www.mancaveradio.com/platform/</link>
		<comments>http://www.mancaveradio.com/platform/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Tue, 22 May 2012 18:24:25 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>cave@mancaveradio.com (Jesse and J. J. Lahey)</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Listen to the Show]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.mancaveradio.com/?p=1364</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[The practical follow-up to Tribes. It starts with a great product, content, or experience. Then it becomes about generosity, other-centeredness, helpfulness … and trust. Courage to walk on fire. Bonus offer. The Practical Follow-Up to Tribes Some time ago, I was hugely inspired by Seth Godin&#8217;s ground-breaking book, Tribes: We Need You to Lead Us. [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p></p><!-- Start Shareaholic LikeButtonSetTop Automatic --><!-- End Shareaholic LikeButtonSetTop Automatic --><p><em><a href="http://www.mancaveradio.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/platform.jpg"><img class="alignright  wp-image-1376" title="platform" src="http://www.mancaveradio.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/platform.jpg" alt="" width="298" height="336" /></a>The practical follow-up to Tribes. It starts with a great product, content, or experience. Then it becomes about generosity, other-centeredness, helpfulness … and trust. Courage to walk on fire. Bonus offer.</em></p>
<h2>The Practical Follow-Up to Tribes</h2>
<p>Some time ago, I was hugely inspired by Seth Godin&#8217;s ground-breaking book, <em><a href="http://www.amazon.com/Tribes-We-Need-You-Lead/dp/1591842336">Tribes: We Need You to Lead Us</a></em>. This past week while reading Michael Hyatt’s new book <em><a href="http://michaelhyatt.com/platform">Platform: Get Noticed in a Noisy World</a></em>, I kept thinking, &#8220;Oh, so that&#8217;s how to put it into action.&#8221;</p>
<p>Both Hyatt and Godin write from the perspective that building a platform and a tribe is (in Hyatt&#8217;s words) &#8220;not about ego or being the center of attention. It is about having something of value to others and finding the most powerful way of getting that message to those who can benefit from it.&#8221; Key to this is generosity, other-centeredness, helpfulness, and earning trust.</p>
<p><em>Tribes</em> changed the way I think. <em>Platform</em> provides the practical how-to’s to bring your vision to life. Hyatt is inspiring, yet down-to-earth and transparent. I would go so far as to say this book is generous &#8230; rather than hiding the secrets of his success to make himself look more impressive, he shares nitty-gritty details such as the specific software he uses and companies/people he has hired to help him along the way.</p>
<div id="attachment_1378" class="wp-caption alignleft" style="width: 203px">
	<img class=" wp-image-1378 " title="Michael Hyatt" src="http://www.mancaveradio.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/Michael_Hyatt.jpg" alt="Michael Hyatt" width="203" height="236" />
	<p class="wp-caption-text">Michael Hyatt</p>
</div>
<p><em>Platform</em> also feels more up-to-date than Gary Vaynerchuck’s bestseller, <em><a href="http://www.amazon.com/Crush-It-Time-Cash-Passion/dp/0061914177">Crush It!: Why NOW Is the Time to Cash In on Your Passion</a></em>. That’s because Gary’s book was mostly focusing on blogs and YouTube, whereas Michael covers Facebook, and perhaps more importantly for newcomers, Twitter. However, <em>Crush It!</em> is still a great book that will convince you of the necessity of building and managing your personal brand, regardless of what your vocation is.</p>
<p>I think I’m proof that Michael’s principles still work in 2012. Gary V started WineLibrary.TV in 2006 and published <em>Crush It!</em> in 2009. In 2009, I had never even heard of Michael Hyatt. I first heard him mentioned in 2010, by my buddy Cody Gascho and then by a speaker at a Dan Miller workshop for writers. I checked out his blog a time or two, eventually signed up for his free ebook, a year later he got some affiliate marketing revenue when I purchased <em>Evernote Essentials</em>, and then more recently I bought his ebooks on writing book proposals and now have bought his new book <em>Platform</em>. It took a long time for him to earn enough trust for me to spend any money with him.</p>
<p>As an interesting side note, based on titles (since I haven’t read them), Hyatt’s first four books appear to be essentially scare tactics… warnings and tips about Y2K and digital privacy. This seems to be his first book in more than a decade. I think it’s inspiring that from that rather weak background, he has developed a major book that will be so helpful to many people.</p>
<p><iframe width="500" height="281" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/qkeicFhhwvU?fs=1&#038;feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>
<h2>It Starts with a Great Product, Content, or Experience</h2>
<p>“It’s time to get the passion back,” Hyatt says. “Push one another and yourself to deliver that you are delighted to offer.” Example: Apple’s Steve Jobs introducing the iPhone with almost no marketing.</p>
<p>Hyatt shares six ways to find the courage you need to make “wow” happen</p>
<ol>
<li>Take a stand for greatness.</li>
<li>Connect with the original vision.</li>
<li>Remind yourself what is at stake. (Why is this so important?)</li>
<li>Listen to your heart.</li>
<li>Speak up. Give voice to your heart and go on the record to defend your wow ideas. If you don’t, who will?</li>
<li>Be stubborn.</li>
<li>Very inspiring, yet down-to-earth and transparent. In fact, he even shares with us the specific software he loves and companies/people he has had good results with.
<ul>
<li>Starts his blogs with an Evernote template and then actually do the writing in ByWord, a stripped down word-processor.</li>
<li>MarsEdit for offline blogging client.</li>
<li>TweetPages for his custom background for Twitter, FB, and YouTube.</li>
<li>Standard Theme for WordPress</li>
<li>Shares specific examples, such as effective media kits.</li>
<li>Writes without editing.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ol>
<h2><em>Then It Becomes about Generosity, Other-Centeredness, Helpfulness, and Earning Trust</em></h2>
<p>“Contrary to what many think, social media rewards generosity, other-centeredness, and helpfulness… They work when there is trust. When they become just another form of spam (violating people’s trust), they fail to be effective.”</p>
<ul>
<li>My example: <a href="http://thelocalmethod.com/">Albert Hathazi</a> is a fellow podcaster whom I trust. Recently he <a href="http://twitter.com/#!/TheLocalMethod">tweeted</a> about a product that he believed in, Noodlesoft Hazel for the Mac. It does several things, but the #1 thing that made it worth it for me is that it automatically deletes files from my Mac’s Trash and Downloads folders when they get old. He wasn’t trying to sell me, he was just sharing a tool that he found.</li>
<li>This is a not just a social media principle &#8212; it’s true for all business, and all of life.</li>
</ul>
<h2><strong><strong> Courage to Walk on Fire</strong></strong></h2>
<p>Hyatt’s metaphor of the firewalk.</p>
<ul>
<li><em>Tribes</em> was inspiring. <em>Platform</em> has some inspiration but is mostly practical how-to. Both are a bit scary if you are early in the process.</li>
<li>“Setting out to develop a platform can be overwhelming and scary. This is so much to learn. What if you make a mistake or look foolish? What if they don’t like you? What if you fail? Let me tell you a secret. Forget all of that. Just like fire walking, the key is to start. Once you take the first step everything else will take care of itself”.</li>
<li>“Here’s the question I always ask when I face a daunting task: ‘What would accomplishing this make possible?’”</li>
</ul>
<h3><strong id="internal-source-marker_0.8960267289076"> Bonus Offer</strong></h3>
<p>To celebrate the launch of Michael Hyatt’s new book <em>Platform: Get Noticed in a Noisy World</em>, Michael is giving away $375.98 worth of free bonus content for those who purchase the book between May 21 and May 25. Complete details are available at <a href="http://michaelhyatt.com/platform">http://michaelhyatt.com/platform</a>.</p>
<p>Bonuses include: Platform Video Jumpstart Program (six sessions), How to Write a Winning Book Proposal (two e-books and two audio sessions), Why NOW is the Best Time Ever to Be an Author (hour-long video), Digital Versions of <em>Platform</em> (audio and eBook), and more.</p>
<p><em>Note: I was invited to review an advance copy of this book. I received the Kindle version for free, but I found it to be well-worth the purchase price, and I have bought a hardback copy for one my colleagues at <a href="http://www.aspendalecommunications.com/">Aspendale Communications</a>. I am not receiving any compensation or commissions from Michael Hyatt or Amazon.</em></p>
