		<itunes:subtitle>The practical follow-up to Tribes. It starts with a great product, content, or experience. Then it becomes about generosity, other-centeredness, helpfulness … and trust. Courage to walk on fire. Bonus offer. The Practical Follow-Up to Tribes </itunes:subtitle>
		<itunes:summary>The practical follow-up to Tribes. It starts with a great product, content, or experience. Then it becomes about generosity, other-centeredness, helpfulness … and trust. Courage to walk on fire. Bonus offer.
The Practical Follow-Up to Tribes
Some time ago, I was hugely inspired by Seth Godin's ground-breaking book, Tribes: We Need You to Lead Us. This past week while reading Michael Hyatt’s new book Platform: Get Noticed in a Noisy World, I kept thinking, "Oh, so that's how to put it into action."

Both Hyatt and Godin write from the perspective that building a platform and a tribe is (in Hyatt's words) "not about ego or being the center of attention. It is about having something of value to others and finding the most powerful way of getting that message to those who can benefit from it." Key to this is generosity, other-centeredness, helpfulness, and earning trust.

Tribes changed the way I think. Platform provides the practical how-to’s to bring your vision to life. Hyatt is inspiring, yet down-to-earth and transparent. I would go so far as to say this book is generous ... rather than hiding the secrets of his success to make himself look more impressive, he shares nitty-gritty details such as the specific software he uses and companies/people he has hired to help him along the way.



Platform also feels more up-to-date than Gary Vaynerchuck’s bestseller, Crush It!: Why NOW Is the Time to Cash In on Your Passion. That’s because Gary’s book was mostly focusing on blogs and YouTube, whereas Michael covers Facebook, and perhaps more importantly for newcomers, Twitter. However, Crush It! is still a great book that will convince you of the necessity of building and managing your personal brand, regardless of what your vocation is.

I think I’m proof that Michael’s principles still work in 2012. Gary V started WineLibrary.TV in 2006 and published Crush It! in 2009. In 2009, I had never even heard of Michael Hyatt. I first heard him mentioned in 2010, by my buddy Cody Gascho and then by a speaker at a Dan Miller workshop for writers. I checked out his blog a time or two, eventually signed up for his free ebook, a year later he got some affiliate marketing revenue when I purchased Evernote Essentials, and then more recently I bought his ebooks on writing book proposals and now have bought his new book Platform. It took a long time for him to earn enough trust for me to spend any money with him.

As an interesting side note, based on titles (since I haven’t read them), Hyatt’s first four books appear to be essentially scare tactics… warnings and tips about Y2K and digital privacy. This seems to be his first book in more than a decade. I think it’s inspiring that from that rather weak background, he has developed a major book that will be so helpful to many people.

http://youtu.be/qkeicFhhwvU
It Starts with a Great Product, Content, or Experience
“It’s time to get the passion back,” Hyatt says. “Push one another and yourself to deliver that you are delighted to offer.” Example: Apple’s Steve Jobs introducing the iPhone with almost no marketing.

Hyatt shares six ways to find the courage you need to make “wow” happen

	Take a stand for greatness.
	Connect with the original vision.
	Remind yourself what is at stake. (Why is this so important?)
	Listen to your heart.
	Speak up. Give voice to your heart and go on the record to defend your wow ideas. If you don’t, who will?
	Be stubborn.
	Very inspiring, yet down-to-earth and transparent. In fact, he even shares with us the specific software he loves and companies/people he has had good results with.

	Starts his blogs with an Evernote template and then actually do the writing in ByWord, a stripped down word-processor.
	MarsEdit for offline blogging client.
	TweetPages for his custom background for Twitter, FB, and YouTube.
	Standard Theme for WordPress
	Shares specific examples, such as effective media kits.
	Writes without editing.



</itunes:summary>
