		<itunes:subtitle>Fueling Up the 5-Stroke Engine: understanding the five ways to get people revved up. Man Hero: “Not Just In Charge of Food Service.” Fueling the 5-Stroke Engine The idea of a 5-stroke engine helps us remember that there are five basic ways that peopl...</itunes:subtitle>
		<itunes:summary>Fueling Up the 5-Stroke Engine: understanding the five ways to get people revved up. Man Hero: “Not Just In Charge of Food Service.”
Fueling the 5-Stroke Engine
The idea of a 5-stroke engine helps us remember that there are five basic ways that people feel revved up by the people they live and work with. Most of us need to receive all five to feel approved, affirmed, respected, and/or loved. But usually, one or two of the “strokes” is most significant, and that’s different for everyone.

If you’re interested in reading a whole book on this topic, many people recommend The 5 Love Languages: The Secret to Love That Lasts by Gary Chapman. Frankly, we just haven’t been interested enough to read a whole book about it.

However, we did read a concise and enjoyable chapter on the topic in Have a New You by Friday by Dr. Kevin Leman. And Andy Andrews also explores the topic in a fun way during a chapter of The Noticer. Based on their “cliff notes,” in this episode we provide a summary of all five strokes, as well as an animal that helps us remember each one:

	Words of affirmation or approval (dog)
	Quality time (canary)
	Gifts (chicken)
	Acts of service (goldfish)
	Physical touch (cat)

Understanding the 5 strokes can help you waste a lot of time and frustration with your wife or girlfriend: you can focus on showing her that you care in ways that make a difference to her, and you can help her understand how to treat you right too. It also can help you connect better with your kids, and even help you influence and inspire -- or at least get along with -- your co-workers.
Man Hero: “Not Just In Charge of Food Service”
Most guys in his shoes would say, “I just run a cafeteria.” But that’s not how Floyd Lee sees it.

“I am not just in charge of food service,” said the director of the Pegasus chow hall in Iraq. “I am in charge of morale.”

Floyd Lee has a vision that inspired his entire food staff -- providing American troops with a respite from the turmoil. "This is my niche,” he said. “I've waited for this job all my life, and here I am in Baghdad."

The Pegasus crew gets their food from the same sources as the other military dining halls -- the basic fare is the standard 21-day Army menu. But they’ve created an atmosphere, a gourmet cooking approach, and a presentation that makes soldiers travel out of their way to eat at Pegasus.

"The time you are in here," said Sgt. David Sammy, "you forget you are in Iraq."

For more on this subject, see Jesse's post "Fueling Their 5-Stroke Engine: How to Win Lovers and Influence Co-workers."</itunes:summary>
