		<itunes:summary>The 4 DISC personality profiles. The 4 primary birth orders. 3 ways to take advantage of this knowledge.

In this episode, Jesse and J. J. discuss how helpful it is to understand the four DISC personality profiles or temperaments:

	Dominant
	Influencing
	Steady
	Conscientious

However, it’s often difficult to remember what the four profiles mean, to identify which of the four profiles is most applicable to someone you know, and sometime even to know which most apply to you. That’s why for years, Jesse and J. J. have found it helpful to also understand the influence that birth order has on people’s personalities … it’s certainly easier to ask a person if they are a middle child than to guess at their DISC profile or ask them to take a DISC assessment.

A great resource for understanding birth order is The Birth Order Book, by Dr. Kevin Leman. Leman suggests that the four personality profiles have a strong correlation to these four primary birth orders:

	Oldest child: Dominant
	Youngest child: Influencing
	Middle child: Steady
	Only child: Conscientious

Of course, there is not always a 1:1 correlation, as many other factors apply. And it would be a mistake to simplistically categorize everyone into one of the four categories. As Kent Julian points out, understanding personality profiles can help you better read yourself and other people, but there is more to a person’s personality than the DISC profiles.

Even so, if you understand the DISC profle and/or birth order of yourself and other people, there are three ways to take advantage of this information for greater success in your work and personal life:


	Play to your strengths: Understanding your personality can help you focus 80% of your efforts on leveraging what you are naturally good at and passionate about. For example, many “I” personalities and youngest children enjoy roles such as sales where they have an opportunity to interact and influence other people … they probably would be unhappy pursuing a career that requires them to spend most of their time sitting at a desk doing accounting.
	Understand and improve your weaknesses: You don’t want to spend all your time working in areas that just aren’t a natural fit for you, but you don’t want to ignore your weaknesses either. Consider spending 20% of your efforts to improve or compensating in those areas. For example, that “I” or youngest child may not enjoy accounting, but they can learn some accounting principles and practices to become a better business person, or else bring in a team member to handle that role.
	Understand other people: Being a quicker “read” on other people can help you be more effective at work and also enjoy better relationships in all areas of your life. It can help you find better ways to work with, communicate with, and influence others. Perhaps even more important, it can help you “lighten up” about things people do that bother you, because you’ll be less likely to take it personally when you realize how their natural temperament works.</itunes:summary>
