		<title>MCR-007: 1-800-GET-A-LIFE</title>
		<link>http://www.mancaveradio.com/dec-14-2011-man-cave-radio/</link>
		<comments>http://www.mancaveradio.com/dec-14-2011-man-cave-radio/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Fri, 16 Dec 2011 17:35:37 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator>cave@mancaveradio.com (Jesse and J. J. Lahey)</dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Listen to the Show]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.mancaveradio.com/?p=331</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[Interview with James Woosley, IT project-management consultant and business coach. Man Toys: Sylvan Sport Go; last-minute Christmas comparison of Kindle Fire vs. Nook Color vs. iPad 2. SportsMan: Tim Tebow and the Broncos; Aaron Rodgers and the Packers. Winning with Kids: “Courageous,” karate, and a bedtime book. The gift that keeps on giving. Men’s depression [...]]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p></p><!-- Start Shareaholic LikeButtonSetTop Automatic --><!-- End Shareaholic LikeButtonSetTop Automatic --><p><em><a href="http://www.mancaveradio.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/JamesWoosley.jpg"><img class="alignright size-full wp-image-336" title="James Woosley" src="http://www.mancaveradio.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/12/JamesWoosley.jpg" alt="James Woosley" width="190" height="190" /></a>Interview with James Woosley, IT project-management consultant and business coach. Man Toys: Sylvan Sport Go; last-minute Christmas comparison of Kindle Fire vs. Nook Color vs. iPad 2. SportsMan: Tim Tebow and the Broncos; Aaron Rodgers and the Packers. Winning with Kids: “Courageous,” karate, and a bedtime book. The gift that keeps on giving. Men’s depression and bipolar disorder. 1-800-GET-A-LIFE. UberMan: The Sidekick.</em></p>
<h2><strong>Man Toys</strong></h2>
<p>The new Sylvan Sport Go is part man-toy hauler, part pop-up camper. And at only 800 pounds, it can be towed by even small cars. Plus, to help out all the guys making last-minute Christmas gift selections, we compare the pros and cons of the three hottest contenders in the tablet market: Kindle Fire vs. Nook Color vs. iPad 2.</p>
<p><a href="http://www.sylvansport.com/">http://www.sylvansport.com/</a></p>
<p><a href="http://www.bestbuy.com/site/Barnes+%26+Noble+-+NOOK+Tablet/3825172.p?id=1218435164232&amp;skuId=3825172">http://www.bestbuy.com/site/Barnes+%26+Noble+-+NOOK+Tablet/3825172.p?id=1218435164232&amp;skuId=3825172</a></p>
<p><a href="http://www.bestbuy.com/site/iPad-Tablets/iPad/pcmcat248300050014.c?id=pcmcat248300050014">http://www.bestbuy.com/site/iPad-Tablets/iPad/pcmcat248300050014.c?id=pcmcat248300050014</a></p>
<p><a href="http://www.apple.com/ipad/">http://www.apple.com/ipad/</a></p>
<h2><strong>SportsMan</strong></h2>
<p>Tim Tebow takes the Broncos from last place to first place, and raises a lot of attention by openly sharing his faith. Will Aaron Rodgers lead the Packers to become the first NFL team to have an undefeated season since the 1972 Dolphins? And will the Colts, winners of two recent Super Bowls, go the entire season without a win?</p>
<h2><strong>Winning with Kids</strong></h2>
<p>Reactions to the movie “Courageous,” a story of cops and fathers. The movie had its good points and bad points, but it was effective in inspiring Jesse to take a couple of new steps toward being a great dad. It may sound simple, but I think my two middle kids will be positively impacted by me 1) taking weekly karate lessons with them, and 2) taking a few minutes at bedtime a couple times each week, to read a chapter  from <em>Preparing for Adolescence</em>, by James Dobson, Ph.D.</p>
<h2><strong>1-800-GET-A-LIFE</strong></h2>
<p>Who says outsourcing can’t solve all your problems? This offshore team is eager to help you start your new life.</p>
<h2><strong>Men at Work</strong></h2>
<p><a href="http://www.WoosleyCoaching.com" target="_blank">James Woosley</a> is project-management consultant specializing in implementation of large-scale computerized systems (such as SAP and PeopleSoft). It’s enjoyable, important work that pays well, but it also requires a huge amount of travel with long stretches of time away from his family family and community. James is also a business coach; he uses his project management skills to help entrepreneur-hopefuls follow a roadmap to launch their businesses successfully.</p>
<h2><strong>Gift That Keeps On Giving</strong></h2>
<p>At this busy time of year, we’re often under pressure to get in the Christmas spirit. It can make a big difference to take note of the things and events in our lives that we’re grateful for … whether big or little, and whether positive, neutral, or even negative. Gratefulness can be a perpetual gift to ourselves, and our example can be a gift to our loved ones.</p>
<p>Inspired by a blog written by Jim Sharon- <a href="http://mensanthology.com/2011/12/06/the-perpetual-gift/" target="_blank">http://mensanthology.com/2011/12/06/the-perpetual-gift/ </a></p>
<h2><strong>Men’s Depression and Bipolar Disorder</strong></h2>
<p>It’s generally not considered “manly” to talk about your problems, especially if they involve any form of mental weakness. But we all go through rough moments of life. Jesse’s brother Zach talks candidly about his struggle six years ago – including an apparent misdiagnosis of bipolar disorder and the long-term effects of the anti-psychotic drug he was prescribed. Learn the surprising way he was able to get his life back, with no recurrences so far in the years since then.</p>
<h2><strong>UberMan: The Sidekick</strong></h2>
<p>Michael Buckminster, the mild-mannered alter-ego of UberMan, is stretched thin from all the travel required by his day-job as an IT project-management consultant.  As a result, our hero is finding it difficult to keep up with fighting crime. And so, he tries out a new sidekick, Stretch. But can the untried duo tackle two villains at once?</p>
<p><em><br />
</em></p>
