		<itunes:subtitle>Man Toys With the right toys, some guys can make a game out of anything. Before hauling away his old refrigerator for recycling, our neighbor Russ lets us shoot it full of lead. Men at Work Jesse interviews Jeff Richardson,</itunes:subtitle>
		<itunes:summary>Man Toys
With the right toys, some guys can make a game out of anything. Before hauling away his old refrigerator for recycling, our neighbor Russ lets us shoot it full of lead.
Men at Work
Jesse interviews Jeff Richardson, basketball coach and teacher at Oolitic Middle School in the land of the Hoosiers. Jesse shares an inspiring quote by Dan Miller, best-selling author of 48 Days to the Work You Love.
Marriage Moment
What’s a woman doing in the Man Cave? Some rules are made to be broken, so Jesse invites in his favorite hottie to help him share a tip on how to score ... er, succeed … with your woman. It seems to work so well that Jesse decides he needs a commercial break.
“More Weight for My Shoulders”
Like many guys, Ray has a hard time letting go of his worries. But there may be good reasons why he is wired this way.
Quote of the Week
"All happy families resemble each other, but each unhappy family is unhappy in its own way.” Cervantes, as quoted in Made to Stick by Chip Heath and Dan Heath.
Wimpmaker Alert
Can we fight poverty without encouraging men to become wimps? Jesse comments on an intriguing guest post on michaelhyatt.com, written by Pat Morley (author of Man in the Mirror).
Fight Club
Dr. David W. Powers shares about how guys beating up on each other at a monthly event has been a healthy experience. Can learning to get hit help a man gain confidence?
History in the Making
Jesse discusses the defeat, capture, and killing of Gaddafi. While he has not been following the news closely, the battle against a dictator inspires Jesse to talk about William Travis and the other heroes of the Alamo who led the fight against Santa Anna.
UberMan Begins
Are superheroes born or made? Either way, they have to learn how to wear their underwear on the outside of their pants. When we first meet UberMan, he is coaching an almost-all-girls basketball team at a small middle school.</itunes:summary>
